  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_3' aria-label=\" Dr. Vimal Sukumar  versus D. Lawrence & Ors. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('3','2025','2025_5_1731_1777','2025INSC622'); ><font size='4'> <strong>DR. VIMAL SUKUMAR <span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>D. LAWRENCE & ORS. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 5 S.C.R. 1731</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 622</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010007502025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : BELA M. TRIVEDI<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, SATISH CHANDRA SHARMA</strong><br> Issue for Consideration The instant appeals are arising out of the two impugned orders dated 27.02.2024 and 12.04.2024 by which the Division Bench of the High Court declared re-election of all the office bearers since it was held that the electoral college itself was flawed and appointed re-elections. Furthermore, it was held that the amendments to the bye-laws had not been carried out in accordance with the procedure prescribed in the Constitution of Church of South India (CSI) and it was held that the Special Meeting of the Synod held on 7th and 8th March 2022 was not duly<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 02-05-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CIVIL APPEAL No. 6264/2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Disposed off</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('3','2025','2025_5_1731_1777','2025INSC622','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a href='